<h1>Datasets &amp; downloads</h1>
<p>Two datasets, normalised on <code>mark_id</code>: the <strong>marks</strong> (metadata, in git) and the
   <strong><code>episodes</code></strong> rows (per-unit, in object storage). The episode rows are published
   <strong>per mark</strong> &mdash; one gzipped CSV for each mark &mdash; so a mark's rows <em>are</em> its file.</p>

<div class="download">
  <h3>The <code>episodes</code> dataset <span class="badge">primary</span></h3>
  <p>Each unit's <em>(state, action, reward)</em> row: its context before the decision (<code>running_value</code>
     and the mark's covariates), what was done (<code>assigned</code>/<code>treated</code>), and the <code>outcome</code>
     that followed. Published <strong>per mark</strong> as a gzipped CSV; join its rows to the mark JSON on the mark id
     for the design and the full effect distribution. (RDD/DiD marks ship a <code>cross-section</code> row per unit;
     ITS marks ship a <code>panel</code> row per series &times; time bucket.)</p>
  <p class="meta">{{.EpisodeTotalRows}} rows total across {{len .EpisodeFiles}} marks · one gzipped CSV per mark<br>
     Columns: {{.ColumnsJoined}} <em>(+ each mark's covariates)</em></p>
  <div class="table-wrap">
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Mark</th><th>Series</th><th>Effect</th><th>Rows</th><th>Download</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
    {{range .EpisodeFiles}}
      <tr>
        <td><code>{{.ID}}</code><br><a href="dossiers/{{.ID}}.html">dossier</a> · <a href="{{$.RepoURL}}/blob/main/marks/{{.ID}}.json">mark JSON</a></td>
        <td>{{.Series}}</td>
        <td>{{.EffectStr}}</td>
        <td>{{.Rows}}</td>
        <td>
          {{if .URL}}<a class="btn secondary" href="{{.URL}}">episodes.csv.gz</a> <span class="meta">{{.Bytes}}</span>
          <br><span class="meta">SHA-256 <code>{{.SHA256}}</code></span>{{else}}&mdash;{{end}}
        </td>
      </tr>
    {{end}}
    </tbody>
  </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="download">
  <h3>Marks <span class="badge">metadata</span></h3>
  <p>One JSON per decision: the design, the effect distribution, the validity dossier, and provenance.
     The full nested marks live in git.</p>
  <p class="meta">{{.MarksZip.Count}} marks · {{.MarksZip.Bytes | bytes}} zipped<br>
     SHA-256 <code>{{.MarksZip.SHA256}}</code></p>
  <div class="actions">
    <a class="btn" href="downloads/marks.zip">Download all marks (zip)</a>
    <a class="btn secondary" href="{{.RepoURL}}/tree/main/marks">Browse on GitHub</a>
  </div>
</div>

<h2>Frozen raw inputs <span class="badge">reproducibility</span></h2>
<p>The original open-data inputs, frozen and content-addressed so every mark re-mints byte-for-byte. You only need
   these to reproduce the marks &mdash; not to use the datasets above. Each carries its own licence.</p>
<div class="table-wrap">
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Source</th><th>Publisher</th><th>Licence</th><th>Size</th><th>Download</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
  {{range .Sources}}
    <tr>
      <td>{{.Title}}<br><code>{{.SourceID}}</code></td>
      <td>{{.Publisher}}</td>
      <td>{{if .LicenceURI}}<a href="{{.LicenceURI}}">{{.Licence}}</a>{{else}}{{.Licence}}{{end}}</td>
      <td>{{if .Bytes}}{{.Bytes | bytes}}{{else}}&mdash;{{end}}</td>
      <td><a href="{{.URL}}">download</a>{{if .OrigURL}} · <a href="{{.OrigURL}}">original</a>{{end}}</td>
    </tr>
  {{end}}
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>
